Title : Caroline Cameron
Text : '''Caroline Cameron''' (born March 23, 1990 in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]) is a Canadian television sportscaster for [[Sportsnet]]. Cameron is the host of the pre-game program ''[[Hockey Central]]'' Tonight, four nights a week, as well as regional intermissions. 

== Career ==
Cameron was a sportscaster and reporter for [[Sportsnet]] from Spring 2012 to February 2014,  ppearing regularly on [[CityNews Channel]]. From February 2014 to March 2016, she lived in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]] and co-anchored the national morning edition of ''[[Sportsnet Central]]'' (formerly named ''Sportsnet Connected'') with [[James Cybulski]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/sportsnet-announces-james-cybulski-and-caroline-cameron-as-new-connected-morning-anchors/|title=Sportsnet Announces James Cybulski and Caroline Cameron as New Connected Morning Anchors|work=Sportsnet.ca}}</ref> Cameron returned to Toronto to co-anchor the national morning edition of ''[[Sportsnet Central]]'' with Carly Agro in 2016 and 2017 and with Eric Thomas in 2017 and 2018. 

Prior to 2016, Cameron provided courtside commentary for Sportsnet's coverage of the Women's [[Rogers cup (tennis)|Rogers Cup]] Canadian Open Tennis tournaments in Toronto and Montreal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bttoronto.ca/videos/4421143189001/|title=Caroline Cameron on her tennis career and Rogers Cup|work=bttoronto.ca}}</ref>  Since 2016, Cameron has hosted and anchored the [[Sportsnet]] daytime coverage of the Rogers Cup [[Canadian Open (tennis)]] tournaments.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://about.rogers.com/2017/08/02/sportsnet-serves-multiplatform-rogers-cup-coverage-starting-august-7/|title=Sportsnet Serves Up Multiplatform Rogers Cup Coverage, Starting August 7|work=Sportsnet.ca}}</ref>  In February 2018, Cameron hosted and called play-by-play for Sportsnet's coverage of Canada v. Croatia in Davis Cup competition.

In February 2018, Cameron hosted Sportsnet's "Olympic Morning" in Toronto for morning coverage of the [[2018 Winter Olympics|XXIII Winter Olympics]] in Pyeongchang, Korea.

Cameron is a KidSport BC ambassador.<ref>http://www.kidsportcanada.ca/british-columbia/team-kidsport/caroline-cameron/</ref> KidSport is a not-for-profit organization that providing financial assistance for sports registration fees for kids 18 and under. Cameron also supports Dementia Friends Canada,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alzheimer.ca/~/media/Files/national/Media-releases/asc_release_09212015_DementiaFriends_e.pdf/|title=Dementia Friends Canada 2015 on World Alheimer's Day|work=Alzheimer.ca|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304221058/http://www.alzheimer.ca/~/media/Files/national/Media-releases/asc_release_09212015_DementiaFriends_e.pdf/|archivedate=2016-03-04|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref> an initiative of the [[Alzheimer Society of Canada]] to increase understanding of dementia to support the many Canadians who already have the disease.

== Education ==
Cameron graduated from the [[University of Western Ontario]] and [[Fanshawe College]]'s joint [http://www.westerncalendar.uwo.ca/Archive/2004%28new%29/WESTERN_FANSHAWE_COLLABORATIVE_DEGREE_DIPLOMA_IN_MEDIA_THEORY_AND_PRODUCTION_302888.html Media Theory and Production] ([https://www.fanshawec.ca/programs-and-courses/program/mtp-media-theory-and-production/current-year Broadcast Journalism]) program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fanshawec.ca/about-fanshawe/news/fanshawe-college-celebrate-its-outstanding-alumni/|title=Fanshawe College Celebrates its Outstanding Alumni|work=Fanshawe.ca}}</ref>

